        "description": [
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "A traditional form of Japanese poetry that originated in the 17th century, the Haiku is characterized by its strict syllable count of 17 syllables. Divided into three lines of 5-7-5 syllables, it is known for its focus on nature and the changing seasons, and features a \"cutting word\" (kireji) that separates or contrasts different parts of the poem."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Typically composed of three lines, a Haiku does not rhyme. The first line, containing 5 syllables, sets the scene or introduces the main subject of the poem. The second line, containing 7 syllables, provides additional details or imagery related to the first line. While the third line contains 5 syllables and concludes the poem, often with a twist or a moment of insight."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "A Haiku is a short form of poetry and provides economy of language by providing a lot with few words. Striving to use the fewest words possible to convey the most meaning, Haiku poets often rely on imagery and metaphor to create a sense of depth and complexity."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Fill in each part of this template to successfully complete your haiku."
